{{NOT|date=August 2018}} {{refimprove|date=August 2018}} {{Infobox college sports rivalry | name = Nebraska–Texas football rivalry | team1_image = Nebraska Cornhuskers logo.svg | team1_image_size = | team2_image = Texas Longhorns logo.svg | team2_image_size = | team1 = [[Nebraska Cornhuskers football|Nebraska Cornhuskers]] | team2 = [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas Longhorns]] | total_meetings = 14 | series_record = Texas leads, 10–4 | first_meeting_date = October 7, 1933 | first_meeting_result = Nebraska 26, Texas 0 | last_meeting_date = October 16, 2010 | last_meeting_result = Texas 20, Nebraska 13 | largest_win_margin = Nebraska, 26–0 (1933) | longest_win_streak = Texas, 6 (2002–10) }}
The '''Nebraska–Texas football rivalry''' was an American [[college football]] [[college rivalry|rivalry]] between the Nebraska Cornhuskers and Texas Longhorns. The rivalry dissolved when Nebraska left the [[Big 12 Conference]] for the [[Big Ten Conference]]. Due to Colorado, Missouri, Nebraska, and Texas A&M leaving the conference, the [[Big 12 Championship Game]] dissolved due to a lack of teams in the conference. The last ever Big 12 Championship game was played between Nebraska and Oklahoma in 2010. The rivalry is known for the tension between the two programs. Almost every game between the two could have gone either way, with Texas stealing many of the victories in heartbreaking fashion. In the 1996 Big 12 Championship game, Nebraska had a four-point lead over Texas until Wane McGarity scored a touchdown for Texas, followed by a late touchdown by Priest Holmes to allow Texas to win, 37–27.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/503093-recap-of-the-nebraska-texas-rivalry|title=Nebraska-Texas, Recap of the Rivalry|work=BleacherReport.com|access-date=January 12, 2016}}</ref>
The [[2009 Big 12 Championship Game]] between Texas and Nebraska ended controversially as the officiating crew added one second to the clock, allowing Texas to score the winning field goal over Nebraska.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/06/sports/ncaafootball/06big12.html?_r=0|title=Texas wins Big 12 in a Wild Finish|work=NYTimes.com|access-date=January 12, 2016}}</ref>
Although most Nebraska fans disagreed with the call, former Nebraska coach [[Tom Osborne]] stated that Texas "won the game fair and square", and that he was at the game in the press box and felt confused when it first had happened.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsday.dallasnews.com/college-sports/texaslonghorns/2010/10/13/20101012-Nebraska-s-Tom-Osborne-On-9804|title=Nebraska's Tom Osborne: On Texas rivalry and leaving the Big 12|work=DallasNews.com|access-date=January 12, 2016}}</ref>
